…. the strong execution of its digitization and retail-led strategy in the Nigerian market informs a positive growth trajectory.  The Managing of Access Bank Plc on Thursday March 17th released 2021 Full Year results through the floor of Nigerian Exchange (The NGX) to the investing communities, which showed that the bank recorded substantial growth in Gross Earnings by 27.1% year-on-year to NGN971.89 billion. This was driven by growth in both the funded and non-funded income segments as the bank was more aggressive in creating risk assets, especially through its digital and retail-based products, which bolstered fees and commission income. On the EPS of NGN4.58 up by 52.2% year-on-year, the board proposed a final dividend of 70kobo per share as against 2020 record of 55 kobo share, which equates to a dividend yield of 7.1% based on the last closing price of NGN9.80 per share on Friday, March 18th 2022 .  The bank recorded an interest income growth of 23.0% year-on-year to NGN601.70 billion in 2021Full Year, buoyed by the uptick in income from investment securities of 31.7% year-on-year to NGN203.68 billion. Similarly, income from loans and advances to customers by 16.4% year-on-year to NGN360.19 billion and banks of 116.8% year-on-year to NGN28.38 billion increased following the double-digit loan growth by 29.3% year-on-year to NGN4.16 trillion, the highest seen so far among Tier-1 peers. The growth across these income lines offset the sole decline in cash and balances with banks by 20.9% year-on-year to NGN9.46 billion.  Interest expense also increased by 32.8% year-on-year to NGN300.24 billion, with a significant spike in the cost of deposit from customers up by 41.1% year-on-year as the bank took on more expensive term deposits to meet its obligations. Consequently, the bank’s Current Account Savings Account (CASA) mix deteriorated to 58.4% in 2021Full Year from 64.6% in 2020Full Year. Likewise, expenses on interest-bearing liabilities up by 77.1% year-on-year and debt securities growth of 12.6% year-on-year increased during the period.  Similar to Tier-1 peers, non-interest income grew significantly by 30.6% year-on-year to NGN329.60 billion, supported by the solid income growth from foreign exchange trading up by126.3% year-on-year to NGN101.10 billion, net fees and commission income up by 26.7% year-on-year to NGN118.60 billion, and bad debt recoveries. This growth in non-funded income further supported the funded income growth, leading to a 21.1% year-on-year expansion in operating income.  Operating expenses increased by 13.7% year-on-year  to NGN371.14 billion in 2021Full Year, as all major contributory lines recorded spikes of personnel expenses by 32.2% year-on-year to NGN96.71 billion, deposit insurance premium of 32.0% year-on-year to NGN20.44 billion, AMCON levy up by 17.1% year-on-year to NGN41.51 billion and non-cash depreciation and amortization charges of 12.3% year-on-year to NGN42.15 billion. Given the more significant year-on-year expansion in operating income than expenses, the bank’s cost-to-income ratio (after accounting for LLEs) improved to 67.7% from 72.2% in 2020Full Year.  Tying it all together, the bank recorded a profit before tax growth of 40.3% year-on-year to NGN176.70 billion. However, PAT notched up higher by 51.1% year-on-year to NGN160.22 billion, given the lower income tax expense by 17.2% year-on-year.  Comment: analysts at Cordros Research said ACCESS’s increasingly strong financial performance and the corresponding increase in payout to shareholders lend credence to our positive outlook on the bank. We envisage positive price reactions in the short to medium term.  According to them, the bank is also one of the fastest-growing banks nationwide, with an increasing footprint across Africa, noting with the strong execution of its digitization and retail-led strategy in the Nigerian market informs analyst view of a positive growth trajectory.